dmesg

The dmesg command in Linux is used to display the kernel ring buffer, which is a log of messages generated by the kernel during the boot process and while the system is running. It is a useful tool for troubleshooting system problems and for monitoring system events.

Here is the basic syntax for the dmesg command:

css
Copy code
dmesg [options]
Here are some commonly used options for the dmesg command:

-c: Clears the kernel ring buffer after displaying its contents.
-n level: Sets the minimum level of kernel messages to display, where level can be a numeric log level or a log level name (e.g., debug, info, warn, err).
-T: Displays the timestamp of each message in a human-readable format.
Here are some examples of how to use the dmesg command:

To display the contents of the kernel ring buffer:
Copy code
dmesg
This command displays the contents of the kernel ring buffer, which is a log of messages generated by the kernel during the boot process and while the system is running.

To clear the kernel ring buffer after displaying its contents:
r
Copy code
dmesg -c
This command displays the contents of the kernel ring buffer and then clears it.

To display only kernel messages with a log level of err or higher:
Copy code
dmesg -n err
This command displays only kernel messages with a log level of err or higher, ignoring messages with lower log levels.

To display the timestamp of each message in a human-readable format:
r
Copy code
dmesg -T
This command displays the contents of the kernel ring buffer, with the timestamp of each message displayed in a human-readable format.

These are just a few examples of how to use the dmesg command in Linux. With its powerful capabilities for displaying kernel messages and system events, dmesg is a useful tool for troubleshooting and monitoring Linux systems.
